he state of the state's constitution. Among the topics addressed are state debt and budgeting practices, legislative redistricting, local government, gambling, conservation, and the process of amending the constitution. Written by knowledgeable professionals, the chapters explain the constitutional provisions in question, including the reasons for their constitutional status; how they have been used and interpreted; and the extent of the gaps between the constitutional provisions and practice. Various proposals for reform are also examined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aConstitutional lawxCongressesxNew York (State)xNew York (State)xConference papers and proceedings. 0aConstitutional lawzNew York (State)vCongresses. 4aNew York/Regional : New York State Government. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : Constitutional Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Politics. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh1 aBenjamin, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin, Gerald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBloustein, Marc C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBopst, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBopst, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBray, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreitbart, Todd A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriffault, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Daniel L., econtributor.